explain the decorator more and the async

Great questions! Let's go deep on both. 👇

Decorators (@client.event)
Imagine you work at a hotel front desk. Guests walk in all day, but you only care about certain types of guests — maybe VIPs.

So you put a special sticker on certain rooms that says "when a VIP arrives, put them HERE."

That's what a decorator does. The @client.event line is the sticker. It tells Discord:

"The function right below me? That's not just any function. It's one that should run when a specific Discord event happens."
Without the @client.event sticker, your on_ready function would just sit there doing nothing. Discord wouldn't know it exists. The decorator connects your function to Discord's event system.

The @ symbol is Python's way of saying "this is a decorator." You'll always see it sitting on the line directly above a function.

Async (async def)
Normally, Python does one thing at a time — like a single cashier at a grocery store. Each customer has to wait for the one in front to finish completely.

But a Discord bot can't work that way. Imagine your bot is in a busy server — 10 people send messages at the same time. If your bot had to fully finish responding to person 1 before even looking at person 2's message, it would be painfully slow.

`async` tells Python: "This function might need to pause and wait for something — like waiting for Discord to respond or waiting for OpenAI to generate an answer. While it's waiting, go ahead and handle other stuff."

Think of it like a waiter at a restaurant. They don't stand at your table waiting for the kitchen to cook your food. They take your order, hand it to the kitchen, and then go serve other tables. When your food is ready, they come back.

That's async — it lets your bot be a smart waiter instead of a single slow cashier.

You'll see the word `await` soon — that's the moment where the bot says "I'm waiting for this, go handle other things in the meantime."

